			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Pulling Hard LDON<a name="27869"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 15 04 3:43 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Excellent guide.  What follows is intended as a supplement -- more detail on some of the mechanics, where your guide spent more time on the concepts and on zone specific advice.
<br />

<br />

<br />
GENERAL ADVICE
<br />

<br />
1.  Learn how and where to place your group.  You want two things.
<br />

<br />
First, you want LOTS of space between you and the rooms you’re pulling.  
<br />

<br />
Second, you want a long straight area before you get to your group.
<br />

<br />
The goal here is for you to KNOW what’s following you before it agros your group.  That way if you have too many, you can fade.  If you’re trying to split, you can fade and see who is pathing where.  Everything described below and in Steppy’s guide works better if you have lots of room and a clear field of vision.
<br />

<br />
Also, if you can swing a big empty room between your group and the mobs, you can kite a bit if necessary.  Several strategies involve mezzing on the run.  What to do if that mez is resisted?  IF you have a big empty room to use, you can kite your pull around the room while you remez.
<br />

<br />
Finally, you want a long straight runway before the mob hits your group.  That’s because many times you will be expecting a mob you mezzed to run back to the group.  If you don’t see him until he rounds a corner and enters the camp, people will take damage before you can mez him.  A caster or a canni’d down shaman can die in the 3 seconds it takes you to cast mez.  But, if there’s a hallway the mob has to run down to get to you, you can start mez as soon as the mob comes into view and ice it before it can hit anyone.
<br />

<br />
BUT, you don’t want too much space.  Things to avoid:
<br />

<br />
- So much space between you and the group that pulls take too long.
<br />
- Too many turns and twists between you and the group, such that you get crunched on the way back.
<br />

<br />
2.  Get used to using the toggle-last-target key.  I believe this is mapped to ` by default – I map mine to Tab.  I will refer to switching between your last two targets as tabbing, just because that’s how I think of it.  If you use a different key, I rely on you to make your own mental edits.
<br />

<br />
3.  Get a Singing Steel Helm.  One of the most invaluable tools you will ever have.  The ability to look closely at a room without getting agro is huge.  Huge.  Huge.  Go camp one or buy one or something.  I just wear the d*mn thing throughout the whole LDON, even though it has squat for stats.  I’m too lazy to take it off :P.
<br />

<br />
Also, remember you can use the Eye to scout while you’re twisting or meleeing.  I often stand in the camp twisting Marr/Muse/Zek while I’m scouting out the next pull with an eye of zomm.  Helps keep the pace up.
<br />

<br />
WAYS TO SPLIT A MULTIPLE SPAWN
<br />

<br />
1.  Learn to split with mez.
<br />

<br />
The basic goal here is to use mez to make one mob stay behind while another mob (or mobs) follows you – either to stagger their arrival in the camp to make crowd control easier or to allow you to use Fading Memories to lose agro on one while still pulling another. 
<br />

<br />
Two spawns:
<br />

<br />
To begin, assume a spawn of two mobs side by side:
<br />
__________
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|``1```2``|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
____|B|___
<br />

<br />

<br />
Where (B) represents you – Bard – and 1 and 2 represent mobs.  This is the easiest arrangement to split and the basis for how you handle larger rooms. 
<br />

<br />
You target #1, then target #2.  Now #1 is stored in your last target buffer.  Mez #2.  #1 will agro and chase you.  Tab on the run so you can OOS/HOS easily when you hit camp.  Then tab again and wait for mez to break.  #2 will come to the camp and you mez.
<br />

<br />
I always tab and wait for the add to come, because I want to #2 mezzed as soon as humanly possible.  I find that if I let myself get distracted, #2 will always kill a caster or a low life tank or bash a cleric out of a heal or something else nasty before I get it locked. 
<br />

<br />
As an alternative, you can fade after #1 gets to the group.  Usually its easier just to have the “planned add,” but sometimes you’re not confident the add will come single – maybe there’s a roamer who might pickup agro, maybe pathing in that room is funky, or maybe you just pulled a named and want no distractions.  
<br />

<br />
Three spawns:
<br />

<br />
__________
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|``2```3``|
<br />
|````1````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
____|B|___
<br />

<br />
The goal here is to convert this room into a two spawn.
<br />

<br />
Target #1, then switch to #2.  Mez #2 and watch -- #1 and #3 should start chasing you.  Turn and run.
<br />

<br />
As you run, tab so that you get #1 on target.  Cast mez on the run.  When it lands, you should have #3 chasing you.  Tow #3 into the camp and fade. 
<br />

<br />
Now, while the group kills #3, you have two choices.  You can stay and help kill #3, then go split the room again just like you’d split a regular two spawn.  Or, you can run back.  In all likelihood, #1 will still be out of the room – maybe mezzed, maybe just starting to path back.  You should be able to bellow at it and bring it back single to mez at the camp.  Entirely up to you which method you prefer.
<br />

<br />
There is also a third option.  You could also refrain from fading at all.  If you do that, here’s what will happen:
<br />

<br />
- #2 will break mez and come to you.  You will need to mez it at the camp.
<br />
- Shortly thereafter, #1 will break mez and come to you.  You will need to mez it also.
<br />

<br />
If you’re confident you can lock both down and hold both down, this method is more efficient – fewer trips out = faster pulling.  If you’re not confident, just fade.
<br />

<br />
Sidebar:  Think about the /con color of a mob when deciding who to mez and who to have the group fight.  Mez lands more reliably on lower con mobs.  So, if 1 and 2 are blue but 3 is white, then you should plan to mez 1 and 2, and let the group fight 3.  If you have 2 mobs of equal con, and one is a clerical mob, that mob is more likely to resist – it self-buffs.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Four spawns:
<br />

<br />
__________
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|````4````|
<br />
|``2```3``|
<br />
|````1````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
____|B|___
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Again, your main goal here is to convert the room into a two or three spawn.  You have two choices – depending on how confident you are in your group’s ability to handle two mobs momentarily unmezzed.
<br />

<br />
Choice #1:  Mez two on the run and tow two unmezzed mobs back to the group.  You target #1, then switch to #2.  Mez #2 and run.  Tab target to #1 and mez on the run.  Then head to group – pivoting and F8 targetting to get #3 or #4 on target.  Mez one more on the run and hit the group with a single unmezzed mob.  
<br />

<br />
Now fade and reacquire agro on the last one you mezzed.  Bring him in and ice him at the group and you’re left with a two spawn back in the original room.
<br />

<br />
Choice #2:  Convert the room to a three spawn and split that later.  Proceed as described above, except that once you have #1 mezzed outside of the room, just fade and wait.  Usually #3 and #4 will path back to the room but #1 will stand there mezzed.  Once you know #3 and #4 are far enough away, break mez on #2 and tow him into the group.  You now have a three spawn to split.
<br />

<br />
2.  Use proximity agro and Kazumi’s Note of Preservation
<br />

<br />
Sometimes you can accomplish impossible pulls by pulling with proximity instead of an agro generating spell.  Take the following diagram:
<br />
__________
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|````4````|
<br />
|```````3`|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|```````2`|
<br />
|````1````|
<br />
____|--|___
<br />
`````--````
<br />
`````--````
<br />
`````--````
<br />

<br />
The lines at the bottom are meant to represent stairs—the idea being that your first mob is RIGHT at the top of some stairs, with other mobs nearby in the room.  Assume also that you don’t have a lot of room between you and the group in which to train a bunch of mobs off and fade.  In order to cast anything – lull or mez – you have to climb to the top of the stairs.  Once you do so, though, you agro 1 which chains to 2 which chains to 3 and 4.  What to do?
<br />

<br />
Try singing Kazumi’s Note of Preservation and then climbing the stairs.  You have two thing going for you here.  First, proximity agro has a smaller chain agro radius than the agro you generate by singing an offensive song or bellowing.  Second, it appears that your chain agro is further reduced by having divine aura on.  I do not know why, but observation seems to show that it is.  So, you have a passable chance in this situation of snagging just 1 or perhaps 1 and 2 – either way a manageable pull.
<br />

<br />
This is also the way to handle pulls made difficult by pathing.  Example:
<br />

<br />
__________
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|```3`4```|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|###2###|
<br />
|###`###|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`1```````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
____|--|___
<br />

<br />
The #s are meant to reflect one of those ditches so common in Guk, with a little bridge over it.  Sometimes in rooms like that, you will find that mob #1 will path over to the bridge and then to the door, instead of directly to the door.  Of course, when he does that, he agros 2, who chain agros 3 and 4.  This is all highly inconvenient.
<br />

<br />
Enter Kazumi’s.  #1 will not follow his scripted pathing if he is within melee range of YOU.  If he is, he will stick to you like glue.  So….  sing Kazumi’s, enter the room, proximity agro him and then go to the wall and out the door.  Do this moving backward if necessary to keep from losing him.  The mob will stay right on top of you and should not path to the bridge if you do this correctly.
<br />

<br />
3.  Be willing to lull when doing so can save you a lot of hassle.
<br />

<br />
Consider the following layout:
<br />

<br />
__________
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`4`````5`|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|````3````|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
|`1`````2`|
<br />
|`````````|
<br />
____|B|___
<br />

<br />
How to pull this room?  Assume that 1 and 2 will chain agro each other, and will chain agro 3.  Assume further that 3 will chain agro 4 and 5.
<br />

<br />
In this situation, lull seems like a worthwhile investment of time.  Try to lull #3.  IF lull works before you critical fail, then quickly tag #1 or #2 and run -- #1 and #2 will follow you, but #s 3, 4, and 5 will stay.  Mez #1 on the run and feed #2 to the group.  You now have an easy three spawn to split.
<br />

<br />
IF, instead, lull critical fails on you – what have you lost?  The whole room is agro, just like it would have been had you mezzed #3 in place.  Mez #3 on the run, then fade and wait to see who goes back.  Split the old fashioned way.
<br />

<br />
4.  Pay attention to agro radii and line of sight.
<br />

<br />
All mobs have a radius beyond which they don’t agro, and a radius beyond which they don’t assist.  You just have to learn these by experimentation.
<br />

<br />
Mobs do not chain agro unless they are in line of sight with another mob.  Line of sight means a line drawn from the center of #1’s avatar to the center of #2s.  A butt poking through a wall doth not line of sight make.
<br />

<br />
Mobs will not agro you unless (1) you cast on them, or (2) you’re in their line of sight – again defined as a line from the center of your avatar to the center of the mob’s.  
<br />

<br />
The Z-axis can break line of sight.  Mobs at the top of a staircase don’t chain agro on mobs at the bottom of a staircase.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Using these rules, you can split mobs and fade more effectively.  If a mob sees inviso, you gotta fade OUTSIDE of its agro radius or when you’re not in its line of sight.  Duck around a corner and fade.
<br />

<br />
If you fade off a pull of three, wait until 1 or 2 have gone outside the third’s agro radius, or left line of sight, before you tag the straggler.
<br />

<br />
Etc.  This is all common sense – and there’s no way to teach it except by experience.  Pay attention to which mobs add when you pull and you will begin to get a feel for agro radii.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Sidebar:  When you fade, there is always a very short period while the mob’s agro is reset.  During that time, even if the mob sees you and you’re in its agro radius, it will not agro you.  IF you duck around a corner in that time, you will not regain agro.  Use this to escape bad pulls of see inviso mobs.  If you turn the corner then fade, the mob may follow around the corner before you fade.  If, instead, you fade just as you hit the corner, then turn, you’re more likely to lose agro completely.
<br />

<br />
WAYS TO AVOID DYING ON THE PULL
<br />

<br />
1.  Get Innate Runspeed 3 AND Swift Journey 2.  Swift Journey 2 brings you almost up to SOW speed indoors.  I find this is enough to keep me ahead of most mobs in hard LDONs.  Usually I can safely turn and monitor my pull.
<br />

<br />
2.  Include Kazumi’s Note of Preservation in your ordinary song lineup.  If you take a wrong turn or fall into one of Guk’s ditches or get stunned, DA can be a lifesaver.
<br />

<br />
3.  Learn the warp spots and avoid them whenever possible.  Certain points in some of the dungeons have warps.  For example, in one Miragle’s layout, there is a huge staircase – looooong way up then loooooooonger way down.  Mobs WILL warp along this staircase.  You know because one second you’re yards ahead of them and the next second they’re hitting you.
<br />

<br />
This sucks for two reasons.  First, you get bludgeoned.  Second, it can make it impossible to lose agro by fading.
<br />

<br />
Only solution is to learn where this happens and avoid pulling through there – either take another path or move the group past the warp point. 
<br />

<br />
WAYS TO AVOID MISTAKES / BAD PULLS
<br />

<br />
1.  Turn your clip plane up as high as you can.  You want to be able to see the ENTIRE room.  Then you cast and watch who moves.  That will tell you if you misjudged agro radii and pulled more than you expected.
<br />

<br />
2.  Watch for agro messages.  This is the “A dazzling oculus unfurls its tentacles and begins to kick your can” message.  If you see one of these for something you didn’t mean to agro, you know you got a bad pull on your hands.  :P
<br />

<br />

<br />
WAYS TO COMMUNICATE WITH THE GROUP
<br />

<br />
1.  Make informational hotkeys.  A standard is the inc message – one mob per message.  I also make another hotkey:  %T will add shortly.  I will mez %T.
<br />

<br />
I use this in those “planned add” situations.  I mez #1 in place, toggle to #2 and run it into the group.  On the way, I hit “Inc %T” to tell them #2 is coming and they should fight it.  I then toggle my target to #1 and hit the “%T will add, I will mez” key to tell them to expect an add and to expect me to mez it.
<br />

<br />
2.  The Mark NPC leadership ability is handy.  I try to train my group with the following rule:  don’t hit a marked mob unless it’s the last mob left standing.  Then, if the pull gets hairy and I don’t have time to do the inc / mez message sequence described above, I just mark my current target and mez it.  MT knows to fight the other target.
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
